-1"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nIn a row of dominoes, tops[i] and bottoms[i] represent the top and bottom halves of the ith domino. (A domino is a tile with two numbers from 1 to 6 - one on each half of the tile.)\nWe may rotate the ith domino, so that tops[i] and bottoms[i] swap values.\nReturn the minimum number of rotations so that all the values in tops are the same, or all the values in bottoms are the same.\nIf it cannot be done, return -1.\n \nExample 1:\n\n\nInput: tops = [2,1,2,4,2,2], bottoms = [5,2,6,2,3,2]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: \nThe first figure represents the dominoes as given by tops and bottoms: before we do any rotations.\nIf we rotate the second and fourth dominoes, we can make every value in the top row equal to 2, as indicated by the second figure.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: tops = [3,5,1,2,3], bottoms = [3,6,3,3,4]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: \nIn this case, it is not possible to rotate the dominoes to make one row of values equal.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= tops.length <= 2 * 104\nbottoms.length == tops.length\n1 <= tops[i], bottoms[i] <= 6\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minDominoRotations(self, tops: List[int], bottoms: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\nfrom math import inf\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minDominoRotations(self, tops: List[int], bottoms: List[int]) -> int:\n        def f(x: int) -> int:\n            cnt1 = cnt2 = 0\n            for a, b in zip(tops, bottoms):\n                if x not in (a, b):\n                    return inf\n                cnt1 += a == x\n                cnt2 += b == x\n            return len(tops) - max(cnt1, cnt2)\n\n        ans = min(f(tops[0]), f(bottoms[0]))\n        return -1 if ans == inf else ans\n```\n\nThis solution defines a helper function `f(x)` that calculates the minimum number of rotations needed to make all elements in either `tops` or `bottoms` equal to `x`. It then checks the minimum rotations needed for the values of the first domino (`tops[0]` and `bottoms[0]`) and returns the result, or `-1` if it's not possible to make all values in one row the same.", "estimated_date": 1552176000000}